Best Practices for Creating Strong Passwords
Use at least 12–16 characters.
Include uppercase letters, lowercase letters, numbers, and special characters.
Avoid using common words, names, or predictable patterns.
Use a unique password for every account.
Enable Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) whenever available.
Consider using a password manager to generate and store strong passwords.
What I Learned
Through this task, I learned that password length and complexity are important factors in creating secure passwords. Short and predictable passwords are easier to crack using brute-force and dictionary attacks, while longer passwords with a combination of characters provide much better protection. I also understood the importance of using unique passwords and enabling Multi-Factor Authentication to improve account security.
Conclusion
This task helped me understand how password strength affects cybersecurity. Strong passwords are essential for protecting personal and professional accounts from unauthorized access. By following password best practices, users can significantly reduce the risk of cyberattacks.
